Hi,

I don't really know if this is expected but the following:

```
var Hello = React.createClass({
    render: function() {
        return <div test={this.props.value} placeholder={this.props.value} data-placeholder={this.props.value}>Hello</div>;
    }
});

React.render(<Hello value="World"/>, document.body);
```

Will lead to 

```
<div placeholder="World" data-placeholder="World" data-reactid=".0">Hello</div>
```

It seems that React did not mount the "test" attribute because it's not standart. But actually it mounted the placeholder attribute while it is not standart too. Is this expected?

So React can mount a div with a placeholder attribute in its current state, but the weird thing is that it can't update this attribute.

```
var Hello = React.createClass({
    render: function() {
        return <div test={this.props.value} placeholder={this.props.value} data-placeholder={this.props.value}>Hello</div>;
    }
});

React.render(<Hello value="World"/>, document.body);
React.render(<Hello value="WorldUpdated"/>, document.body);
```

This will produce:

```
<div placeholder="World" data-placeholder="WorldUpdated" data-reactid=".0">Hello</div>
```

See http://jsfiddle.net/kb3gN/10968/

Don't know how this is supposed to work but I think the current behavior is kind of unexpected ;)
